    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-03-20T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-03-20T03:00:00-05:00" n="14"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d14">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/2513</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PTN1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-03-20T09:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 20, 1916, 9 a. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 5 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>604. Government sustained last night vote nearly 7 to 1; probably means two or
                    more new members ministry representing democratic bloc, one minister of
                    munitions.</p>
                <p>Declaration of war with Germany before long seems indicated, but it substantially
                    exists now.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>[For the text of a resolution introduced in the Reichstag by the Socialist
                        Party, calling on the Government to “do everything in its power to bring
                        about an early peace,” see telegram No. 3654, March 22, 1916, received March
                        23, from the Ambassador in Germany, <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref
                            target="#pg_210">page 210</ref>.]</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
